# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adams-onís-treaty
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The **1803 United States Senate election in Massachusetts** was held in February 1803.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Incumbent Senator Jonathan Mason, who had been elected to fill the unexpired term of Benjamin Goodhue, did not run for a full term in office.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The Massachusetts General Court deliberated and elected State Senator and former diplomat John Quincy Adams, son of former President John Adams, on the fourth ballot.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] This is the first election in the history of the United States where the winner of the Senate in Massachusetts would eventually become president of the United States.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] This is also the first election to feature a candidate who would eventually become president of the United States.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Benjamin Goodhue was elected Senator from Massachusetts in 1796.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] However, he resigned and retired from politics in 1800.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] In his place, the legislature elected State Senator Jonathan Mason.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] When Mason's term expired in 1803, he declined to stand for re-election.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The Senate ratified the choice of Adams on a single unanimous ballot.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams served one term in the Senate, though he would resign months early after the Federalist legislature prematurely voted not to award him a second term.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams quickly drifted away from the Federalist Party, partly over his differences with Pickering.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] After joining the Democratic-Republicans, he would go on to serve as Secretary of State and later as President of the United States from 1825 to 1829.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1808.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican candidate James Madison defeated Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney decisively.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Madison had served as Secretary of State since President Thomas Jefferson took office in 1801.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, who had declined to run for a third term, threw his strong support behind Madison, a fellow Virginian.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Sitting Vice President George Clinton and former Ambassador James Monroe both challenged Madison for leadership of the party, but Madison won his party's nomination and Clinton was renominated as vice president.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists chose to re-nominate Pinckney, a former ambassador who had served as the party's 1804 nominee, again alongside Rufus King.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the unpopularity of the Embargo Act of 1807, Madison won the vast majority of electoral votes outside of the Federalist stronghold of New England.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton received six electoral votes for president from his home state of New York.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first of two instances in American history in which a new president was selected but the incumbent vice president won re-election, the other being in 1828.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley, who had chaired the congressional nominating caucus during the 1804 presidential election, made a call for the 1808 caucus to the 146 Democratic-Republican members of the United States Congress and Federalist allies.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 89 to 94 members of Congress.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] With the support of outgoing President Thomas Jefferson, Secretary of State James Madison won the presidential nomination over opposing candidates James Monroe and Vice President George Clinton.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus voted to give the vice presidential nomination to Clinton over his main opponent John Langdon, although Clinton's supporters believed Clinton would receive the Federalist Party's presidential nomination.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists instead nominated Charles Cotesworth Pinckney that September.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] A committee of fifteen members was selected to manage Madison's campaign.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Seventeen Democratic-Republicans in Congress opposed Madison's selection and the caucus system whose authority to select presidential and vice-presidential candidates was disputed.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe, who was supported by dissident and majority leader John Randolph, was nominated by a group of Virginia Democratic-Republicans (Old Republicans), and although he did not actively try to defeat Madison, he also refused to withdraw from the race.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was also supported by a group of New York Democratic-Republicans for president even as he remained the party's official vice presidential candidate.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist caucus met in September 1808 and re-nominated the party's 1804 ticket, which consisted of General Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina and former Senator Rufus King of New York.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only time in American history that a defeated major party renominated its losing ticket for a second time.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The election was marked by opposition to Jefferson's Embargo Act of 1807, a halt to trade with Europe that disproportionately hurt New England merchants and was perceived as favoring France over Britain.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, Jefferson was still very popular with Americans generally and Pinckney was soundly defeated by Madison, though not as badly as in 1804.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received few electoral votes outside of New England.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney retained the electoral votes of the two states that he carried in 1804 (Connecticut and Delaware), and he also picked up New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and three electoral districts in North Carolina besides the two electoral districts in Maryland that he carried earlier.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Except for the North Carolina districts, all of the improvement was in New England.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe won a portion of the popular vote in Virginia and North Carolina, while the New York legislature split its electoral votes between Madison and Clinton.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The popular vote totals used are the elector from each party with the highest total of votes.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The vote totals of Kentucky, North Carolina, and Tennessee appear to be incomplete.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The **1808 United States Senate election in Massachusetts** was held on June 2, 1808.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] This unusually early election was called after incumbent Federalist John Quincy Adams broke with his party over the Embargo Act of 1807.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The Federalist legislature elected State Senator James Lloyd, Jr. to the term beginning in March 1809.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] John Quincy Adams, son of former Federalist president John Adams, was elected senator by the Massachusetts legislature as a Federalist in 1803.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] His six-year term was scheduled to expire in March 1809.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] However, Adams supported President Thomas Jefferson's foreign policy during the Napoleonic Wars, including the Louisiana Purchase and Embargo Act of 1807.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams was the lone Federalist in Congress to vote for the Non-importation Act of 1806.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] In response to Adams's continued distance from Federalist orthodoxy, the Federalist legislature in Massachusetts held this early election for the United States Senate term beginning in March 1809.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams resigned immediately following his defeat, triggering a special election for the remainder of his term on June 9.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams soon formally joined the Democratic-Republicans and was appointed Minister to Russia by President James Madison.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/1808-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams was later Secretary of State in the Cabinet of James Monroe and was elected President of the United States in 1824.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The **Adams–Onís Treaty** was an agreement between Spain and the United States, signed February 22, 1819, by John Quincy Adams and Luis de Onís respectively.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The US acquired Florida while renouncing claims to Spanish Texas and establishing its first transcontinental boundary.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The provisions of the treaty remained in full effect only until August 24, 1821, when the Treaty of Córdoba acknowledged Mexican independence from Spain.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] In the 1828 Treaty of Limits (Mexico–United States), the border defined by the Adams–Onís Treaty was recognized as the boundary between Mexico and the US, although following the 1845 Texas annexation, it was amended again by the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The Adams–Onís Treaty was formally terminated in 1902.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Pinckney's Treaty of 1795 established borders between the United States and Spanish Florida, but expansion by American settlers into this region led to ongoing disputes between the countries.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The 1803 Louisiana Purchase caused further arguments over whether the new boundary to the south ran along the Sabine River, or the Rio Grande.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The outbreak of the Peninsular War in 1807 and the Spanish American wars of independence in 1808, undermined Madrid's ability to retain its American territories.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Between 1810 and 1813, the US took advantage to annex West Florida in piecemeal fashion from the Mississippi east to the Perdido River, the modern state boundary with Alabama.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] During the first of the Seminole Wars from 1817 to 1818, the US occupied the rest of Florida, presenting John Quincy Adams, then Secretary of State, an opportunity to negotiate favorable terms.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] His policy was to simultaneously avoid foreign commitments, but to also establish the US as the preponderant power on the North American continent.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] This required the elimination as far as possible of competing Spanish, Russian and British interests in the region, and extending the limits of American power to the Pacific.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] These principles were set out in more detail in the 1823 Monroe Doctrine.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] By 1819, Spain was prepared to accept the loss of Florida in exchange for a firm border in Texas.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] For his part, Adams saw an opportunity to remove outstanding Spanish claims in the Western United States, and establish the US' first transcontinental boundary.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Despite their increasingly tenuous position in New Spain, the Madrid government was prepared to make concessions, hoping to regain them at a later date.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Negotiations were held in Washington, D.C., led by Adams for the United States, and Luis de Onís, the Spanish ambassador, resulting in a final agreement of 16 articles.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Key provisions included Article 2, transferring East and West Florida to the US, and Article 3, defining the southern border between the two countries, while Spain withdrew historic claims to the Oregon Country.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Other terms included an agreement by the US government to compensate American settlers for alleged losses inflicted by the Spanish, the continuation of Pinckney's Treaty, and most favoured nation privileges for Spanish traders in Pensacola and St.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Senate approved the treaty unanimously on February 24, 1819, but Madrid delayed ratification until October 1820, hoping to dissuade the US from supporting anti-Spanish revolutionaries.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] As a result of the delay, the Senate had to vote a second time, at which point Henry Clay and others demanded the cession of Texas in addition.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] This proposal was defeated and the treaty officially made effective on February 22, 1821.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] In accordance with Article 11, the US government set up a commission to handle claims made by private American citizens against Spain, which distributed around $5 million prior to its dissolution in 1824.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] For the United States, this Treaty (and the Treaty of 1818 with Britain agreeing to joint control of the Pacific Northwest) meant that its claimed territory now extended far west from the Mississippi River to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] For Spain, it meant that it kept its colony of Texas and also kept a buffer zone between its colonies in California and New Mexico and the U.S. territories.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Many historians consider the Treaty to be a great achievement for the U.S., as time validated Adams's vision that it would allow the U.S. to open trade with the Orient across the Pacific.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Informally this new border has been called the "Step Boundary", although the step-like shape of the boundary was not apparent for several decades—the source of the Arkansas, believed to be near the 42nd parallel north, was not known until John C.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Frémont located it in the 1840s, hundreds of miles south of the 42nd parallel.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] While Mexico was not initially a party to the Adams–Onís Treaty, in 1831 Mexico ratified the treaty by agreeing to the 1828 Treaty of Limits with the U.S.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] With the Russo-American Treaty of 1824, the Russian Empire ceded its claims south of parallel 54°40′ north to the United States.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] With the Treaty of Saint Petersburg in 1825, Russia set the southern border of Alaska on the same parallel in exchange for the Russian right to trade south of that border and the British right to navigate north of that border.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] This set the absolute limits of the Oregon Country/Columbia District between the 42nd parallel north and the parallel 54°40′ north west of the Continental Divide.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] By the mid-1830s, a controversy developed regarding the border with Texas, during which the United States demonstrated that the Sabine and Neches rivers had been switched on maps, moving the frontier in favor of Mexico.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] As a consequence, the eastern boundary of Texas was not firmly established until the independence of the Republic of Texas in 1836.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] It was not agreed upon by the United States and Mexico until the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo in 1848, which concluded the Mexican–American War.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] That treaty also formalized the cession by Mexico of Alta California and today's American Southwest, except for the territory of the later Gadsden Purchase of 1854.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Another dispute occurred after Texas joined the Union.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty stated that the boundary between the French claims on the north and the Spanish claims on the south was Rio Roxo de Natchitoches (Red River) until it reached the 100th meridian, as noted on the John Melish map of 1818.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] But, the 100th meridian on the Melish map was marked some 90 miles (140 km) east of the true 100th meridian, and the Red River forked about 50 miles (80 km) east of the 100th meridian.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Texas claimed the land south of the North Fork, and the United States claimed the land north of the South Fork (later called the Prairie Dog Town Fork Red River).
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] In 1860, Texas organized the area as Greer County.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The matter was not settled until a United States Supreme Court ruling in 1896 upheld federal claims to the territory, after which it was added to the Oklahoma Territory.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty gave rise to a later border dispute between the states of Oregon and California, which remains unresolved.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] Upon statehood in 1850, California established the 42nd parallel as its constitutional de jure border as it had existed since 1819 when the territory was part of Spanish Mexico.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] In an 1868–1870 border survey following the admission of Oregon as a state, errors were made in demarcating and marking the Oregon-California border, creating a dispute that continues to this day.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] In 2020, a hoax appeared in Spain according to which, in 2055, the Adams–Onís Treaty would expire and Florida would be returned to Spain by the United States, which is false.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The previous Anglo-American Convention of 1818 meant that both American and British citizens could settle land north of the 42nd parallel and west of the Continental Divide.
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The United States now had a firm foothold on the Pacific Coast and could commence settlement of the jointly occupied Oregon Country (known as the Columbia District to the British government).
[src:adams-onís-treaty/adams-onís-treaty] The Russian Empire also claimed this entire region as part of Russian America.
